<Document>
<name>Highway 12 — A Journey Through Time</name>
<description><![CDATA[<h2>Highway 12 — A Journey Through Time</h2><p><i>Utah, USA · UT-12, Torrey to Panguitch via Boulder, Escalante, Bryce</i></p><p><b>200 km of slickrock, hoodoos, knife-edge ridge driving, and three national parks/monuments.</b></p><table style='font-family:sans-serif'><tr><td><b>Approx. length:</b></td><td>180 km (112 mi)</td></tr><tr><td><b>Drive time:</b></td><td>4–5 hrs without stops; ideally 2–3 days</td></tr><tr><td><b>Best season:</b></td><td>April–October</td></tr><tr><td><b>Watch out for:</b></td><td>High passes (Boulder Mtn ~2,900 m); Hogback section has drops on both sides; flash floods in slot-canyon country</td></tr><tr><td><b>Track points:</b></td><td>369</td></tr></table><hr><p>Highway 12 wasn't fully paved until 1985 — the village of Boulder received its mail by mule until 1940. The road crosses some of the most rugged country in the lower 48: Capitol Reef's eastern flanks, the 12,000 km² Grand Staircase-Escalante, and Bryce Canyon's pink-orange amphitheater. The Hogback section between Boulder and Escalante runs along a literal ridgeline with hundreds of feet of drop on both sides. An All-American Road in name and substance — there is no comparable single route in the western US.</p><h3>Scenic points marked on this route:</h3><ul><li><b>Larb Hollow overlook</b> — 2,896 m on Boulder Mountain. The Henry Mountains fill the eastern horizon 80 km away — the last range in the lower 48 to be added to American maps (1872).</li><li><b>Lower Calf Creek Falls</b> — 5.6 km round-trip hike through a sandstone canyon to a 39 m waterfall. One of the great hidden hikes of the Southwest.</li><li><b>The Hogback</b> — 7 km of asphalt on a sandstone ridge with steep drops on both sides. No guardrails. White-knuckle if the wind is up. Pull off and walk to the edge.</li><li><b>Head of the Rocks overlook</b> — Panorama of slickrock domes stretching to the Henrys — 'Mars with juniper,' a geologist friend says.</li><li><b>Bryce Canyon — Inspiration / Sunset Points</b> — Largest concentration of hoodoos on Earth. Best at sunrise from Inspiration Point; full-moon walks in summer.</li><li><b>Red Canyon</b> — Scarlet limestone arch tunnels you drive through. Lesser-known and uncrowded; mountain biking trails nearby.</li></ul><hr><p><i>Track geometry is interpolated between named waypoints — use a routing service to snap to actual road for navigation. Waypoints, scenic POIs, and notes are reliable.</i></p>]]></description>
